<p>I am writing a Java code to save the output in text file. I have written a code and it overwrites the text file and saves only the last answer. However I need to save the text file without overwriting, similar like log files. When I use the code to print output in console window (By using system.out.print) I get complete output. But when I use log.print it prints only the last result in the file. Basically I want all the directories and files to be printed and saved in a text file. But when I run the program it saves only the last file or directory in text file. I need to get complete output without overwriting the text file. Please help me. I am attaching the code as well.</p>  <pre><code>import java.io.File;  import java.io.IOException; import java.io.PrintStream; import java.util.logging.Logger;  public class GetFile  {     private static final Logger log1 = Logger.getLogger(GetFile.class.getName());     private static final Logger log = Logger.getLogger(GetFile.class.getName());        public static void main(String[] args)      {         log1.info("Execution Started\n\n");         File currentDir = new File(args[0]); // current directory         displayDirectoryContents(currentDir);         log1.info("Ended\n\n");     }      public static void displayDirectoryContents(File dir)      {          try          {               PrintStream log = new PrintStream("testLog.txt");             System.setOut(log);              File[] files = dir.listFiles();             for (File file : files)              {                 if (file.isDirectory())                  { //                  System.out.println("directory:" + file.getCanonicalPath());                     log.println("directory:" + file.getName());                     displayDirectoryContents(file);                 }                  else                  { //                  System.out.println("     file:" + file.getCanonicalPath());                     log.println("     file:" + file.getName());                 }             }         }          catch (IOException e)          {             e.printStackTrace();         }     } } </code></pre>  <p>I have taken a part of code from stackoverflow.</p>  <p>Please help me. Thanks in advance</p>